</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="121.[189,1399,1637,1853]" pageId="121" pageNumber="122">
<taxonomicName authority="Grootaert &amp; Shamshev, 2012" authorityName="Grootaert &amp; Shamshev" authorityYear="2012" box="[189,457,1637,1663]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Nanodromia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="121" pageNumber="122" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinulosa" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[189,457,1637,1663]" italics="true" pageId="121" pageNumber="122">Nanodromia spinulosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[466,558,1638,1664]" pageId="121" pageNumber="122" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is closely related to 
<taxonomicName authority="Grootaert &amp; Shamshev" authorityName="Grootaert &amp; Shamshev" authorityYear="2003" box="[805,1192,1637,1663]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Nanodromia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="121" pageNumber="122" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="taksin">
<emphasis box="[805,910,1637,1663]" italics="true" pageId="121" pageNumber="122">N. taksin</emphasis>
Grootaert &amp; Shamshev
</taxonomicName>
but the latter has the hind tibia modified with rows of squamiform setae. In 
<taxonomicName authority="Grootaert &amp; Shamshev, 2012" authorityName="Grootaert &amp; Shamshev" authorityYear="2012" box="[899,1048,1675,1701]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Nanodromia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="121" pageNumber="122" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinulosa" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[899,1048,1675,1701]" italics="true" pageId="121" pageNumber="122">N. spinulosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1058,1152,1676,1702]" pageId="121" pageNumber="122" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
the hind tibia is not so strongly curved and swollen and there is only an anterior row of spinule-like setae on the apical half instead of squamiform setae. Additionally, the new species resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="Grootaert &amp; Shamshev" authorityName="Grootaert &amp; Shamshev" authorityYear="2003" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Nanodromia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="121" pageNumber="122" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="narmjeud">
<emphasis box="[1093,1242,1751,1777]" italics="true" pageId="121" pageNumber="122">N. narmjeud</emphasis>
Grootaert &amp; Shamshev
</taxonomicName>
that has also the basal third of mid femur swollen and pubescent. However, in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Grootaert &amp; Shamshev" authorityYear="2003" box="[1251,1398,1789,1815]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Nanodromia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="121" pageNumber="122" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="narmjeud">
<emphasis box="[1251,1398,1789,1815]" italics="true" pageId="121" pageNumber="122">N. narmjeud</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the mid tibia is curved, while it is straight in 
<taxonomicName authority="Grootaert &amp; Shamshev, 2012" authorityName="Grootaert &amp; Shamshev" authorityYear="2012" box="[714,861,1827,1853]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Nanodromia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="121" pageNumber="122" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinulosa" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[714,861,1827,1853]" italics="true" pageId="121" pageNumber="122">N. spinulosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[869,959,1827,1853]" pageId="121" pageNumber="122" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
